---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';
---

<CaseStudyLayout
    title="IHOPU Website | Jared Smith"
    projectTitle="IHOPU Website"
    type="UI/UX Design & Front-end Development"
    tagline="A complete redesign that doubled time-on-site and grew application starts by 28% in the first semester."
    client="International House of Prayer University"
    role="UI/UX Designer & Front-end Developer"
    timeline="20 weeks"
    platform="WordPress (custom theme)"
    coverImage="/assets/ihopu-website.jpg"
    nextHref="/work/hills-vet"
    nextTitle="Hill's Browse by Condition"
>
    <div class="case-study-section">
        <span class="case-study-section__label">The Problem</span>
        <h2 class="case-study-section__title">A website working against enrollment</h2>
        <div class="case-study-section__body">
            <p>IHOPU's website hadn't been meaningfully updated in over five years. The institution had grown significantly — new programs, a larger student body, a more developed community culture — but the website communicated almost none of it. Prospective students found the information architecture confusing, the visual design dated, and the mobile experience barely functional.</p>
            <p>Application starts were below target. Analytics showed a predictable story: prospective students were landing on the site, struggling to find what they needed, and leaving before they got to the application. The admissions team was supplementing the website with phone calls that should have been unnecessary.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-two-col">
        <div class="case-study-insight">
            <p class="case-study-insight__number">78%</p>
            <p class="case-study-insight__label">Mobile bounce rate on the existing site — the primary device for prospective students</p>
        </div>
        <div class="case-study-insight">
            <p class="case-study-insight__number">5+ yrs</p>
            <p class="case-study-insight__label">Since the last meaningful redesign — the institution had outgrown its website</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-section">
        <span class="case-study-section__label">Research</span>
        <h2 class="case-study-section__title">Listening to the people who had already said yes</h2>
        <div class="case-study-section__body">
            <p>Before touching the design, I spent significant time listening. The best source of insight was students who had enrolled — they remembered what their decision process felt like, what they'd searched for, and what the website had and hadn't given them.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Stakeholder interviews with administration, admissions staff, and faculty (8 sessions)</li>
                <li>Surveys of 40 current students and recent enrollees about their pre-enrollment research process</li>
                <li>3 months of web analytics reviewed for entry points, drop-off pages, and conversion paths</li>
                <li>Competitive audit of 8 seminary and ministry school websites</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Two things surfaced as critical. First, prospective students needed to quickly understand IHOPU's unique mission and community culture — not just the academic catalog. Second, the application process itself felt opaque and overwhelming. Multiple students described clicking "Apply" and immediately closing the tab.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-image-block">
        <div class="placeholder-block"><p>Current-state audit and research synthesis — placeholder</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-section">
        <span class="case-study-section__label">Design Process</span>
        <h2 class="case-study-section__title">Rebuilding the architecture from the user's journey</h2>
        <div class="case-study-section__body">
            <p>I restructured the information architecture around the prospective student's decision journey: Who is IHOPU? What do you offer? What is life like there? How do I apply? This sounds obvious in retrospect — but the existing site was organized around the institution's internal departments, not the visitor's questions.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Full IA restructure with card sorting and tree testing (18 participants)</li>
                <li>Brand refresh — preserving core identity while modernizing visual execution</li>
                <li>New visual design system: type scale, color system, component library</li>
                <li>Wireframes for all page templates (14 unique layouts)</li>
                <li>Custom WordPress theme built from scratch with clean, semantic markup</li>
                <li>Redesigned application flow with step indicators and plain-language guidance</li>
            </ul>
            <p>I owned both design and development on this project — building the WordPress theme gave me the ability to implement the design precisely rather than handing off and hoping. The result was a tight correspondence between the design intent and the live site.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-image-block">
        <div class="placeholder-block"><p>Wireframe templates and design system — placeholder</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-section">
        <span class="case-study-section__label">The Solution</span>
        <h2 class="case-study-section__title">A site that tells the story and opens the door</h2>
        <div class="case-study-section__body">
            <p>A complete redesign built around a clear narrative arc — who IHOPU is, what they offer, what life looks like there, and how to take the next step. The homepage led with community and mission rather than an academic catalog. Program pages were restructured to answer the questions students actually asked.</p>
            <p>The application flow was simplified from a single overwhelming page to a guided, multi-step experience with clear progress indicators and plain-language explanations at each stage. Student testimonials and community photography — the highest-engagement content on the old site — were woven throughout rather than siloed on a single "Campus Life" page.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-image-block">
        <div class="placeholder-block"><p>Final site — homepage and program page — placeholder</p></div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-section">
        <span class="case-study-section__label">Results</span>
        <h2 class="case-study-section__title">A website that did the work the admissions team couldn't</h2>
        <div class="case-study-section__body">
            <p>Results tracked across the first full semester post-launch showed meaningful movement on every metric the admissions team cared about. The site had gone from an obstacle to an asset.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-two-col">
        <div class="case-study-insight">
            <p class="case-study-insight__number">2×</p>
            <p class="case-study-insight__label">Increase in average time on site from prospective students</p>
        </div>
        <div class="case-study-insight">
            <p class="case-study-insight__number">28%</p>
            <p class="case-study-insight__label">Increase in application starts in the first semester after launch</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study-two-col">
        <div class="case-study-insight">
            <p class="case-study-insight__number">41%</p>
            <p class="case-study-insight__label">Drop in mobile bounce rate — from 78% down to 41%</p>
        </div>
        <div class="case-study-insight">
            <p class="case-study-insight__number">↑</p>
            <p class="case-study-insight__label">Admissions team reported a notable drop in "basic info" inquiry calls</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</CaseStudyLayout>
